<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1881-05-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1881-05-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="721" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d721">
                    <head>No. 717.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Heap</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-05-27"><hi rend="italic">May</hi> 27,
                            1881</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 32.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your dispatch No. 4, of the
                        4th instant, touching the protest of American citizens against the payment
                        of taxes upon their property, in anticipation of a forced loan by the
                        Government of Turkey, and to inform you that, in this matter, you may act in
                        concert with the representatives of the other powers at Constantinople, as
                        proposed in your dispatch.</p>
                    <p>I am, sir, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>JAMES G. BLAINE.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>